WEBVTT

00:00.959 --> 00:02.794
ANDY: <i>Previously on </i>NYPD Blue...

00:02.877 --> 00:04.087
-Good morning.
-Ouch.

00:05.505 --> 00:07.507
I had a little trouble
at McGowan's last night.

00:07.716 --> 00:09.843
ANDY: Lucy Welker, says a guy grabbed her,

00:09.926 --> 00:11.511
pulled her into the alley,
and started punching.

00:11.594 --> 00:12.929
Do you know him from
around the neighborhood?

00:13.054 --> 00:14.514
No, I've never seen him before.

00:14.681 --> 00:17.600
Lucy Welker is supposed
to testify for me this afternoon

00:17.726 --> 00:18.727
in a felony-murder case.

00:19.019 --> 00:20.103
What's the case?

00:20.270 --> 00:21.646
LORI: It's the Aberdeen warehouse fire.

00:21.771 --> 00:23.857
-Is that with this Korensky guy?
-LORI: Right.

00:24.024 --> 00:26.151
Torched one of his warehouses
for the insurance.

00:26.401 --> 00:27.902
Who was that assaulted you this morning?

00:28.069 --> 00:29.863
I've seen him around the office.

00:30.113 --> 00:32.574
He told me
that if I testified against Simon...

00:32.824 --> 00:34.325
(SOBBING) ...he'd cut my throat.

00:34.451 --> 00:38.163
-Sir, if I could just explain...
-I received an anonymous allegation

00:38.288 --> 00:41.207
that you were working at McGowan's.
I've confirmed that allegation.

00:41.458 --> 00:44.419
As a result, I've referred the matter
to internal affairs.

00:44.544 --> 00:45.712
You're gonna send me to them?

00:45.879 --> 00:48.298
Michael's dad has filed
a petition with the court.

00:48.548 --> 00:50.759
He's requested a hearing
to modify the placement order.

00:50.842 --> 00:53.219
Craig killed Michael's mother.
He nearly killed his aunt.

00:53.303 --> 00:56.097
You can't tell me the courts are gonna
seriously consider giving Michael to him.

00:56.347 --> 00:58.808
Pending psychological evaluations
of the parties,

00:58.975 --> 01:02.937
I am granting petitioner
one supervised visit a week.

01:04.064 --> 01:07.734
(UPBEAT MUSIC PLAYING)

01:15.950 --> 01:17.118
(MUSIC FADES)

01:17.243 --> 01:19.537
-(KNOCK ON DOOR)
-ANDY: Yeah?

01:19.746 --> 01:20.997
Morning, Andy.

01:22.290 --> 01:23.333
Morning.

01:23.958 --> 01:25.335
-What do you got there?
-Nothing.

01:26.377 --> 01:28.797
-That looked like the patrol guide.
-Yeah.

01:29.172 --> 01:31.633
-What are you looking up?
-Yeah, just checking up on something.

01:31.716 --> 01:32.926
Yeah? What is it? Maybe I'll know.

01:35.386 --> 01:38.139
-I'm studying for the sergeant's exam.
-You are?

01:39.057 --> 01:40.308
Just to see how I'd do.

01:41.351 --> 01:42.352
Why?

01:42.644 --> 01:45.021
All these guys run around here
like they got something on you

01:45.146 --> 01:47.565
'cause they hit the books
for a couple of weeks.

01:47.690 --> 01:49.234
I figure I'd take a crack at it.

01:49.734 --> 01:51.903
-Good for you.
-Yeah.

01:52.153 --> 01:55.323
Listen, uh, how you doing with your thing?

01:55.782 --> 01:58.243
-We'll see.
-You hear from the trustee yet?

01:58.535 --> 02:00.745
I'm, uh, meeting with him later today.

02:01.830 --> 02:04.457
-I'll hear him out, weigh my options.
-ANDY: Right.

02:04.874 --> 02:07.252
You're on your way up. I'm on my way down.

02:07.377 --> 02:08.628
You don't know what's gonna happen.

02:08.920 --> 02:13.550
Yeah, well, regardless of what happens,
I ain't exactly glory-bound.

02:14.050 --> 02:17.554
You're a good cop, Medavoy.
Nobody can take that away from you.

02:20.515 --> 02:21.975
Sergeant Sipowicz.

02:24.769 --> 02:25.812
I like that.

02:30.650 --> 02:35.071
(THEME MUSIC PLAYING)

03:31.669 --> 03:33.379
(THEME MUSIC FADES)

03:35.840 --> 03:38.092
(UPBEAT MUSIC PLAYING)

03:42.680 --> 03:43.932
(MUSIC FADES)

03:44.224 --> 03:45.391
(KNOCK ON DOOR)

03:45.558 --> 03:48.728
Lieutenant, I wanted to ask
about taking off a little early today.

03:49.229 --> 03:51.981
-I have family court with my foster son.
-What's going on?

03:52.273 --> 03:54.067
It's a final-custody determination.

03:54.734 --> 03:56.527
-When do you need to leave?
-BALDWIN: 2:30.

03:57.570 --> 03:59.822
-It's your time. Do what you gotta do.
-Thank you.

03:59.989 --> 04:01.532
THOMAS: Is there an end in sight
to this thing?

04:01.866 --> 04:02.867
Hopefully.

04:03.409 --> 04:05.495
-I hope it works out.
-Yeah, me, too.

04:10.208 --> 04:12.794
-Could I speak to you for a second, boss?
-Come in.

04:16.965 --> 04:18.091
(DOOR SHUTS)

04:19.300 --> 04:21.219
Uh. (CHUCKLES)

04:21.844 --> 04:23.888
I... I've been doing some soul-searching

04:24.347 --> 04:26.891
off the things you said
regarding my working in the bar,

04:27.475 --> 04:28.559
and you were right.

04:28.726 --> 04:30.561
I definitely didn't take it
seriously enough.

04:31.646 --> 04:34.399
There are good reasons
for the rule against it.

04:35.483 --> 04:37.694
P.S... (CHUCKLES) I get it.

04:42.323 --> 04:44.742
Uh, what I... what I'm wondering
in light of that

04:44.951 --> 04:48.579
is if it's really necessary
to stay with this kind of punishment.

04:49.706 --> 04:50.873
Unfortunately, it is.

04:53.209 --> 04:55.378
I can't afford a 30-day rip, boss.

04:55.837 --> 04:57.547
I understand you're gonna
feel it, Medavoy.

04:57.839 --> 04:58.881
That's the point.

04:59.173 --> 05:02.510
I can't fix the prevailing attitudes
in this squad if the only kinds of

05:02.635 --> 05:04.220
disciplinary measures I impose
are the ones

05:04.345 --> 05:05.805
that can be comfortably ignored.

05:05.930 --> 05:09.851
(SIGHS) Lieutenant,
my prevailing attitude is fixed.

05:10.226 --> 05:11.477
It's already fixed.

05:12.478 --> 05:13.479
I'm sorry.

05:16.190 --> 05:19.652
(INTENSE MUSIC PLAYING)

05:25.992 --> 05:27.035
(MUSIC FADES)

05:27.493 --> 05:28.703
Mr. Foreman,

05:29.037 --> 05:31.622
have you followed my instructions
to reconsider each other's opinions?

05:31.706 --> 05:32.707
We have, Your Honor.

05:32.790 --> 05:34.709
JUDGE KEPLER: Have you attempted
to re-examine your views?

05:34.792 --> 05:36.627
-FOREMAN: We have.
-Do you remain at an impasse?

05:36.878 --> 05:37.879
We do.

05:38.129 --> 05:39.630
Is it your opinion
that further deliberation

05:39.756 --> 05:41.257
will not yield a verdict?

05:41.382 --> 05:44.344
-It is, Your Honor
-JUDGE KEPLER: Counsel, approach.

05:50.016 --> 05:52.352
Judge, the people believe
in the strongest possible terms

05:52.518 --> 05:54.145
that the jury should
continue deliberating.

05:54.228 --> 05:56.064
It's been a week, Counselor.

05:56.147 --> 05:58.274
Given current circumstances,
we don't believe that is sufficient

05:58.358 --> 05:59.942
amount of time to declare a mistrial.

06:00.026 --> 06:01.903
Well, I'm curious as to what
Miss Munson's referring to

06:02.070 --> 06:04.447
-as "current circumstances."
-Well, you could start with the fact

06:04.572 --> 06:05.948
that our chief witness was assaulted.

06:06.157 --> 06:09.160
There is absolutely no evidence
linking my client to this alleged assault.

06:09.243 --> 06:11.537
And I resent Miss Munson's
implying anything to the contrary.

06:11.662 --> 06:12.914
Is there any reason that this witness

06:12.997 --> 06:14.749
wouldn't be able to testify
at the second trial?

06:15.041 --> 06:17.668
Quite honestly, I don't know
how much more she can endure, Your Honor.

06:17.835 --> 06:20.129
Well, if it's a matter of endurance,
Miss Munson,

06:20.380 --> 06:23.216
I think your office together with
the New York City Police Department,

06:23.424 --> 06:27.095
should be able to do whatever is necessary
to keep her safe and available.

06:27.845 --> 06:28.971
Step back.

06:33.393 --> 06:36.354
Given what I believe to be the futility
of further deliberations,

06:36.479 --> 06:38.689
I am, indeed, declaring a mistrial.

06:38.815 --> 06:40.358
GARY: Your Honor, at this time,

06:40.525 --> 06:43.736
the defense respectfully makes
an application for bail to be set.

06:43.820 --> 06:44.904
The people oppose.

06:44.987 --> 06:47.156
My client has been incarcerated
for six months.

06:47.323 --> 06:48.699
He has roots in the community.

06:49.033 --> 06:51.744
Under no definition of the term
does he represent a flight risk.

06:51.953 --> 06:55.331
You're making this application based on
length of pre-trial incarceration?

06:55.540 --> 06:58.876
That's correct, Your Honor.
Mr. Korensky's entitled to a speedy trial.

06:59.168 --> 07:01.629
He's been denied the companionship
with wife and children.

07:01.796 --> 07:04.966
-Just as they've been denied his...
-The man is on trial for felony murder.

07:05.133 --> 07:09.720
His family and his business represent
significant roots in the community.

07:10.012 --> 07:12.390
He also has significant contacts
in Russia and Israel,

07:12.557 --> 07:14.642
which clearly make him a flight risk.

07:14.934 --> 07:16.853
I'm gonna disagree
with you there, Miss Munson.

07:17.270 --> 07:20.106
Given the length of these proceedings,
I think we're obliged to weigh

07:20.273 --> 07:23.025
the impact of continued
incarceration pending trial.

07:23.317 --> 07:26.320
Defendant's motion for bail is granted.
It's set at one million dollars.

07:26.946 --> 07:29.574
The jury is dismissed
with the court's thanks.

07:29.740 --> 07:31.033
And we stand adjourned.

07:31.367 --> 07:32.618
(GAVEL BANGS)

07:33.035 --> 07:35.288
-(INDISTINCT CHATTER)
-(PENSIVE MUSIC PLAYING)

07:35.496 --> 07:36.706
(WHISPERING INDISTINCTLY)

07:40.626 --> 07:42.420
(UPBEAT MUSIC PLAYING)

07:48.259 --> 07:49.510
(MUSIC FADES)

07:49.760 --> 07:52.597
-What does it mean?
-LORI: It means there'll be another trial.

07:53.139 --> 07:55.433
-And I have to testify again?
-Yeah.

07:56.184 --> 07:59.020
-I'm not gonna be able to do that.
-I'll be right there with you, Lucy.

07:59.145 --> 08:01.230
LUCY: I don't even see why you'd want me
to testify again.

08:01.355 --> 08:02.565
Obviously, they didn't believe me.

08:02.815 --> 08:04.984
All it takes is one person
to hang a jury, Lucy.

08:05.109 --> 08:06.944
I think most of those people
did believe you.

08:07.069 --> 08:10.239
-You gotta finish what you started.
-When would the new trial be?

08:10.656 --> 08:12.074
We would push to accelerate it.

08:12.283 --> 08:14.869
Barring anything unforeseen,
I'm thinking sometime in February.

08:15.077 --> 08:18.080
-See, I have plans for during February.
-JOHN: What kind of plans?

08:18.206 --> 08:20.791
I'm going with a group tour
to Scotland and Wales.

08:21.000 --> 08:24.378
We might be able to compensate you
for any expenses involved in rescheduling.

08:24.545 --> 08:25.713
But I don't want to reschedule.

08:25.880 --> 08:29.592
I want to go to Scotland and Wales
and take a side trip to the Lake District,

08:29.675 --> 08:31.969
and I don't want to be doing this anymore.

08:32.053 --> 08:35.306
Lucy, you know how important it is
that Korensky gets what's coming to him.

08:35.515 --> 08:37.642
Then why doesn't anybody else
have to do what I'm doing?

08:37.808 --> 08:39.185
-Like who?
-Like Ike...

08:40.895 --> 08:42.063
or anyone.

08:42.396 --> 08:44.106
-Who's Ike?
-Uh, the brother.

08:44.649 --> 08:46.442
I'm not saying that he knew anything.

08:47.401 --> 08:48.528
We'll talk to him.

08:48.694 --> 08:52.156
He was never anywhere near the warehouse.
I'm sure he doesn't know anything.

08:55.409 --> 08:59.247
(UPBEAT TENSE MUSIC PLAYING)

09:03.000 --> 09:04.168
(MUSIC FADES)

09:04.335 --> 09:05.836
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

09:06.212 --> 09:08.798
-Hey, how you guys been?
-Hey, Baldwin.

09:09.882 --> 09:12.468
-Uh, you got a second?
-Sure.

09:19.642 --> 09:22.270
-Are you doing buy-and-bust these days?
-Yeah, why?

09:22.520 --> 09:24.397
There's somebody I'd like you
to buy into if you could,

09:24.480 --> 09:25.481
his name is Craig Woodruff.

09:25.690 --> 09:27.275
-He a player?
-Either he'll be holding,

09:27.358 --> 09:29.569
or if he thinks he can make a buck,
he'll pull something together.

09:31.112 --> 09:32.488
How come you want us going after him?

09:32.613 --> 09:34.532
He murdered his wife,
then beat it at trial.

09:34.657 --> 09:37.159
He beat his wife's sister
to within an inch of her life.

09:37.535 --> 09:39.245
He drops off for a while,
suddenly resurfaces

09:39.328 --> 09:41.038
trying to get custody of his son.

09:41.706 --> 09:43.082
How do drugs figure into this?

09:45.668 --> 09:47.003
All right, I'll level with you.

09:47.837 --> 09:50.131
I've been the boy's foster parent.
I care about this kid.

09:50.631 --> 09:52.425
You realize it'll take time
to set this up.

09:52.800 --> 09:53.926
We gotta get the guy ID'd,

09:54.051 --> 09:55.511
then it's a crapshoot
if he's even holding.

09:55.636 --> 09:57.555
If he's not, then try him the next day.

09:58.556 --> 10:00.975
Look, you're the first guy
we'd do a favor for,

10:01.100 --> 10:02.351
but we put the hours in on this,

10:02.518 --> 10:04.478
and we gotta be willing to
if we want to collar him,

10:05.021 --> 10:06.772
our boss is gonna want to know why.

10:07.273 --> 10:08.482
Well, maybe you...

10:09.275 --> 10:11.235
maybe you can manage
not to have it take that long.

10:11.944 --> 10:13.029
How can we do that?

10:13.988 --> 10:15.865
There's more than one way
to find drugs on a guy, right?

10:16.490 --> 10:18.951
Hey, Baldwin, if you're asking
what I think you're asking,

10:19.201 --> 10:20.369
we can't do it.

10:20.453 --> 10:22.079
I don't want you to do anything
you're uncomfortable with.

10:22.455 --> 10:24.915
-Yeah, we can't doing that.
-Yeah, no, no.

10:25.124 --> 10:26.667
Don't worry about it.

10:34.759 --> 10:37.178
(UPBEAT MUSIC PLAYING)

10:42.058 --> 10:43.309
(MUSIC FADES)

10:43.643 --> 10:46.062
THOMAS: We're getting you a nice room
at the Holiday Inn on 57th Street.

10:46.312 --> 10:47.313
I don't care.

10:47.730 --> 10:50.066
It's just that that's where
they give us a break on rooms.

10:50.191 --> 10:52.860
And... it's a secure location.

10:53.277 --> 10:55.863
There'll be a detail
of two officers with you at all times.

10:56.030 --> 10:58.157
We'll do our best to have at least
one of them be a female.

10:58.741 --> 11:00.868
-It's not gonna be you?
-I'll be there as much as I can.

11:01.535 --> 11:03.037
THOMAS: Detective Ortiz
and Detective Murphy

11:03.120 --> 11:06.582
-also will be with you some of the time.
-Do I have to eat in my room?

11:06.791 --> 11:08.959
No way. We go to restaurants,
wherever you want.

11:09.210 --> 11:11.295
With certain location considerations.

11:11.504 --> 11:13.422
-I can't go to work, though.
-THOMAS: No.

11:13.589 --> 11:16.133
But you will be compensated
for lost income.

11:16.342 --> 11:17.843
Can I see my sister?

11:18.052 --> 11:20.221
You can, but we'd rather
you didn't go to her house.

11:20.304 --> 11:22.056
If you want to meet her in a restaurant,
that's fine.

11:22.139 --> 11:24.433
I have to be able to go to church.

11:26.394 --> 11:27.645
No problem.

11:30.147 --> 11:32.525
Why don't you take her to the hotel
and get her squared away?

11:32.650 --> 11:34.610
Come on, Lucy, Let's get you situated.

11:38.197 --> 11:40.825
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

11:42.868 --> 11:47.248
-Hey, fancy meeting you here.
-Hi, Ike.

11:47.707 --> 11:49.667
We're going this way. Come on.

11:54.046 --> 11:56.757
Hey, promise me you'll wait for me.
I'll be out in ten years.

11:59.093 --> 12:00.511
I'm not feeling very well.

12:02.138 --> 12:03.806
-(BREATHES DEEPLY)
-RITA: Sit down for a second.

12:03.889 --> 12:05.307
Andy, I'll be right there.

12:07.518 --> 12:10.146
-My pressure's been high lately.
-RITA: Okay, just relax.

12:10.396 --> 12:11.939
I feel like it's something to do
with my heart.

12:12.022 --> 12:13.190
Want to go to the emergency room?

12:13.315 --> 12:16.777
-No, but maybe I could go see my doctor?
-Sure.

12:16.986 --> 12:18.988
Why don't we call ahead
and let them know we're coming.

12:19.071 --> 12:21.699
Is it possible
for Detective Clark to take me?

12:22.074 --> 12:24.118
I'm sorry.
I don't want to be a baby about it,

12:24.368 --> 12:26.704
just for now,
if it could be Detective Clark.

12:26.829 --> 12:29.373
Yeah, sure.
Just tell Andy to go ahead without me,

12:29.457 --> 12:30.791
and I'll call him from the doctor's.

12:30.875 --> 12:33.127
Let the boss know what's going on.
Come on.

12:35.880 --> 12:37.339
Want me to bring the car around?

12:42.470 --> 12:45.055
-So, what's she doing here?
-She's under police protection.

12:45.514 --> 12:47.099
-IKE: On account of my brother?
-Right.

12:48.559 --> 12:49.560
She shouldn't worry.

12:49.643 --> 12:51.520
You expect me to believe
that he didn't have her beat up?

12:52.104 --> 12:53.773
Yeah, 'cause it's the truth.

12:53.981 --> 12:55.733
What can you tell me about the arson, Ike?

12:55.816 --> 12:57.526
Now, why are you so sure it was an arson?

12:57.985 --> 13:01.030
-They found a gasoline can.
-Doesn't mean it was my brother.

13:01.155 --> 13:03.532
What happened? Business was bad,
he went for the insurance?

13:03.616 --> 13:04.909
(SCOFFS) Business was bad.

13:05.034 --> 13:07.036
We're looking right now
to open a store in Paramus.

13:07.620 --> 13:09.413
We know he was in trouble with the IRS.

13:09.663 --> 13:13.292
We know that he stiffed at least two
of the wholesalers he deals with.

13:13.375 --> 13:15.127
Well, those were disputes
over merchandise, period.

13:15.294 --> 13:17.046
-ANDY: He did it before, Ike.
-Nah, never.

13:17.296 --> 13:20.007
He's got a history of using force
to intimidate people.

13:20.508 --> 13:21.592
Let me tell you something.

13:22.051 --> 13:24.470
My brother puts the food on the table
for a lot of people.

13:24.553 --> 13:26.639
He's not a please and thank you guy,
so be it.

13:27.306 --> 13:30.100
You trying to make him out to be
a monster, 100 percent wrong.

13:30.768 --> 13:32.311
Since you stand up for him so good,

13:32.478 --> 13:34.730
-I'm guessing he trusted you.
-Why shouldn't he trust me?

13:34.980 --> 13:37.149
Did he trust you with his plans
to burn down the warehouse?

13:37.483 --> 13:40.402
-What plan?
-What'd you do? Pad the inventory,

13:40.528 --> 13:42.822
so when the warehouse went up
the payoff would be bigger?

13:43.072 --> 13:44.573
You might find this hard to believe,

13:44.990 --> 13:46.951
but I'm not somebody who'd
do something like that.

13:47.326 --> 13:51.872
Ike, are you under the impression
that a mistrial means that the DA's office

13:51.997 --> 13:54.583
would back off in prosecuting this case?

13:55.084 --> 13:57.461
At a certain point, they figure
they got a loser on their hands.

13:57.711 --> 13:59.839
Not till hell freezes over.

14:01.674 --> 14:03.926
(UPBEAT MUSIC PLAYING)

14:07.972 --> 14:09.932
-Thank you for taking me.
-Sure.

14:12.726 --> 14:13.727
Lucy...

14:14.436 --> 14:15.771
-Let's go back inside.
-LUCY: What's wrong?

14:16.063 --> 14:17.648
JOHN: I have to make a phone call.

14:18.983 --> 14:23.070
-(GUNSHOTS)
-(SCREAMING)

14:23.988 --> 14:25.614
-(GUNSHOT)
-(GROANS)

14:25.865 --> 14:27.950
(TIRES SCREECHING)

14:32.037 --> 14:34.081
Adam, Robert, Boy. Adam, Robert, Boy.

14:34.915 --> 14:37.084
Adam, Robert, Boy. Adam, Robert, Boy.

14:40.212 --> 14:41.797
-(RADIO STATIC)
-15th Squad to central "K."

14:41.881 --> 14:43.090
Shots fired, perp down.

14:43.215 --> 14:45.801
Second perp fled in an older,
white, two-door Cadillac.

14:45.968 --> 14:48.846
Partial New York registration
"Adam, Robert, Boy."

14:49.054 --> 14:52.224
-Put a rush on a bus, 2nd Avenue and 10th.
-FEMALE VOICE: <i>10-4 15th Squad...</i>

14:52.600 --> 14:54.768
Lucy, you're okay.

14:55.477 --> 14:57.938
(TENSE MUSIC PLAYING)

15:15.497 --> 15:16.665
(MUSIC FADES)

15:16.874 --> 15:18.500
-How you doing, John?
-I'm okay.

15:18.584 --> 15:19.585
What happened?

15:19.835 --> 15:21.879
The guy came towards us, firing.
I fired back.

15:22.212 --> 15:24.798
-What about the driver?
-John got a partial plate.

15:26.133 --> 15:28.177
There's an alarm going out
city-wide every half hour.

15:28.344 --> 15:29.845
-I have the auto squad running it.
-Good.

15:30.095 --> 15:32.222
-The DOA's got no ID.
-What was he carrying?

15:32.431 --> 15:35.059
A nine millimeter.
The serial number's filed down.

15:35.184 --> 15:37.645
Maybe the lab can bring it in
after ballistics is done.

15:38.938 --> 15:41.148
You have to see psych services,
not that it wasn't justified.

15:41.273 --> 15:42.775
It's just that I want you
giving it its due.

15:43.025 --> 15:44.276
Can I do it tomorrow?

15:45.110 --> 15:46.362
I'm fine, honest.

15:46.946 --> 15:48.572
-First thing tomorrow.
-Yeah, I promise.

15:48.906 --> 15:50.324
That's good work, Detective.

15:53.035 --> 15:55.788
-Are you sure you're okay?
-I'm fine.

15:57.539 --> 15:58.791
Just give me a minute.

16:04.546 --> 16:05.547
How you holding up?

16:06.674 --> 16:08.634
(SIGHS) I don't know.

16:09.843 --> 16:11.804
Look, Lucy, we're gonna find out
who these guys were.

16:11.887 --> 16:13.889
We lay it at the feet of Korensky,
he's done.

16:15.057 --> 16:16.058
Ready?

16:16.225 --> 16:18.310
I'm gonna take her back to the house.
I'll meet you there.

16:29.863 --> 16:33.826
(UPBEAT MUSIC PLAYING)

16:38.872 --> 16:40.332
(MUSIC FADES)

16:40.499 --> 16:43.043
This guy knows what he's talking about,
all right? He's a trustee.

16:43.168 --> 16:45.629
He's been in and out of trial rooms,
how many years is it, Rick?

16:46.338 --> 16:47.673
More than I like to be reminded of.

16:48.173 --> 16:50.426
-CARL: Tell him what you told me.
-Take the rip.

16:51.343 --> 16:53.220
-Just like that?
-Just like that.

16:53.846 --> 16:57.182
-I don't see me deserving a 30-day rip.
-RICK: Nobody's saying that you do.

16:57.474 --> 16:58.726
Is that with the almond paste?

16:59.643 --> 17:01.854
Then I... I don't understand
why I have to take it.

17:01.937 --> 17:03.147
-Rick.
-RICK: You take it' cause if you go

17:03.230 --> 17:04.440
to the trial room, you run the risk

17:04.523 --> 17:06.191
it's gonna be a lot worse
than the 30 days.

17:06.358 --> 17:07.359
-Rick!
-What?

17:07.860 --> 17:09.945
Is that with the almond paste
underneath the fruit?

17:10.904 --> 17:12.031
Like worse how?

17:12.322 --> 17:15.534
Like instead of 30 days,
you get 60 days or a year's probation.

17:15.951 --> 17:17.536
Or they could flop you back
into the uniform.

17:17.661 --> 17:19.204
-They could do that?
-RICK: Right.

17:20.164 --> 17:22.166
-Take it, Carl.
-CARL: Oh, no. I don't want it.

17:22.249 --> 17:24.376
I just wanted to know
if there's almond paste in it.

17:24.460 --> 17:26.045
I don't know
if there's almond paste in it.

17:26.295 --> 17:27.504
(FIST SLAMS)

17:27.629 --> 17:31.592
You know what? I don't care.
There is no way in the world

17:31.717 --> 17:33.969
that I deserve a 30-day rip
for what I did.

17:34.720 --> 17:36.555
And I want my day in court to say that.

17:37.681 --> 17:40.017
If that's what you want,
that's what it is.

17:40.267 --> 17:42.144
We'll have a lawyer. I'll be there.

17:42.978 --> 17:44.480
I'm just telling you,
you're taking a chance.

17:44.730 --> 17:46.774
Good, I'll take the chance.

17:47.816 --> 17:50.110
(UPBEAT MUSIC PLAYING)

17:54.865 --> 17:56.075
(MUSIC FADES)

17:56.241 --> 17:58.535
-Hey, what's up?
-Can we talk somewhere?

17:58.952 --> 17:59.953
BALDWIN: Yeah.

18:02.122 --> 18:04.875
There were parent-teacher conferences
at Michael's school this morning.

18:05.167 --> 18:06.877
Yeah, I know, I made arrangements
to go after work.

18:07.002 --> 18:09.630
Well, Craig showed up.
He met with Michael's teachers.

18:10.047 --> 18:11.340
Well, is the judge gonna do something?

18:11.465 --> 18:13.717
-BOBBI: I don't know.
-He's not allowed to just show up.

18:13.842 --> 18:15.677
No, he's not, but his lawyers
are gonna say

18:15.761 --> 18:17.304
this was just him taking an interest.

18:17.429 --> 18:19.306
And since they'll say you
weren't able to be there,

18:19.473 --> 18:21.433
I don't think they're gonna
come down on him all that hard.

18:21.642 --> 18:23.936
Wait... wait a minute.
How did he even know to go there?

18:24.019 --> 18:25.104
He got in touch with the school.

18:25.437 --> 18:27.106
So he's not waiting
on any rulings from the court.

18:27.189 --> 18:28.732
He's just moving in
on this kid no matter what.

18:28.857 --> 18:30.901
I know from the school
that Michael was upset.

18:31.026 --> 18:32.027
Is that a surprise?

18:32.152 --> 18:34.530
I think you should do
whatever you can to settle him down

18:34.655 --> 18:36.031
and not inflame the situation.

18:36.156 --> 18:39.493
Look, this is a 14-year-old kid.
A smart 14-year-old kid.

18:39.868 --> 18:41.829
He knows better than anybody
what's in store for him

18:41.954 --> 18:43.705
if this son of a bitch worms
his way back in.

18:43.831 --> 18:45.999
I think the two of you
have to resign yourselves

18:46.083 --> 18:48.752
to Craig being back in the picture,
at least to some extent.

18:49.169 --> 18:50.170
That's... that's great,

18:50.295 --> 18:52.297
and what about the administration
for children's services?

18:52.673 --> 18:54.341
What kind of services
are you administrating here?

18:55.217 --> 18:56.510
I'm doing the best that I can.

18:56.635 --> 18:59.138
I get told about things
either last minute or after the fact.

18:59.346 --> 19:01.598
But I have no right to complain.
I'm not even a party to the action.

19:01.723 --> 19:03.267
According to the law, that's right,
you're not.

19:03.392 --> 19:04.309
And according to you?

19:04.560 --> 19:07.980
I'm trying to help you, Baldwin,
but all I am is a caseworker.

19:08.105 --> 19:10.691
That's right.
You're just doing what you're told.

19:10.899 --> 19:13.068
No one told me to come here and tell you.

19:13.318 --> 19:15.571
Oh, well,
thanks for sticking your neck out.

19:15.904 --> 19:17.072
You're welcome.

19:19.825 --> 19:21.160
I'm not the enemy, you know.

19:24.872 --> 19:27.249
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

19:34.840 --> 19:37.134
Sipowicz, can I talk to you a second?

19:38.218 --> 19:39.469
Yeah, what's going on?

19:43.807 --> 19:45.517
You might want to look out
for Jones a little bit.

19:45.767 --> 19:46.852
Why is that?

19:47.186 --> 19:49.021
He's got a thing with the father
of this foster kid.

19:49.146 --> 19:51.607
-ANDY: Right
-He asked me and my partner to flake him.

19:52.566 --> 19:54.443
-He said that?
-That was the general idea.

19:54.526 --> 19:56.945
-You sure that's what he meant?
-I've been in narcotics nine years,

19:57.029 --> 19:58.739
I know when I'm being asked
to make a guy dirty.

19:58.822 --> 20:01.033
-Let me talk to him.
-I know we can hide it.

20:01.158 --> 20:02.993
I mean, whatever he's going through,
he's a right guy.

20:03.243 --> 20:05.037
-Thanks for coming to me.
-Well, just warn him,

20:05.120 --> 20:06.121
he keeps going with this,

20:06.205 --> 20:08.624
-he's gonna get himself jammed up.
-No. I'll straighten him out.

20:09.333 --> 20:12.294
-And we never had this conversation?
-Right.

20:17.424 --> 20:20.344
Hi, I'm Lucy Welker's sister.
I'd like to speak to whoever's in charge.

20:20.427 --> 20:22.179
Yes, of course,
let me find the lieutenant for you.

20:22.387 --> 20:23.513
(PLACES RECEIVER)

20:23.847 --> 20:24.932
Janet, is there anything wrong?

20:25.015 --> 20:27.267
Yeah, there's plenty wrong
but I don't want to talk to you about it.

20:27.351 --> 20:28.352
I want to talk to your supervisor.

20:28.769 --> 20:31.021
I'm Lieutenant Bale.
Why don't you just step into my office?

20:33.899 --> 20:35.025
Why don't you join us, Detective?

20:37.027 --> 20:39.905
This business with my sister
has got to stop. It's over now.

20:40.113 --> 20:43.075
It's the District Attorney's office
that's requiring your sister to testify.

20:43.283 --> 20:45.577
Well, we're gonna see about that.
I don't think anybody has the right

20:45.661 --> 20:46.828
to require my sister to go through

20:46.912 --> 20:48.914
-what she's been going through.
-She's a material witness.

20:49.039 --> 20:51.375
Please, don't throw legal jargon at me,
Lieutenant.

20:51.667 --> 20:54.795
I know any number of high-powered
attorneys who'd be more than happy to sue

20:54.920 --> 20:56.922
the District Attorney's office
and the police department,

20:57.422 --> 20:59.049
including Detective Clark, personally,

20:59.216 --> 21:01.551
-for what's been done to my sister.
-What's been done to me?

21:01.885 --> 21:03.720
Darling, I'm doing my level best
to get you out of here.

21:03.845 --> 21:05.889
Why don't you go wait by
that bench and wait five more minutes,

21:05.973 --> 21:07.683
and then you can come back
to Basking Ridge with me.

21:07.766 --> 21:09.351
We can't allow her to leave the state.

21:09.685 --> 21:11.895
Are you aware
that my sister has a heart condition?

21:12.104 --> 21:14.064
I'm aware she was taken
to the doctor this morning.

21:14.439 --> 21:17.109
Okay, then. We'll provide whatever
medical documentation's necessary

21:17.234 --> 21:18.735
to show that Lucy can't do this.

21:19.069 --> 21:21.113
-Sure she can.
-Excuse me?

21:21.405 --> 21:23.073
She was great on the stand.
Stood her ground...

21:23.156 --> 21:25.617
And what happened for all that
the jury couldn't make up their minds.

21:25.701 --> 21:27.786
-Sometimes that happens.
-And sometimes an innocent,

21:27.869 --> 21:31.623
vulnerable, not-well person
can't be put through an ordeal

21:31.748 --> 21:34.710
so you and your prosecutor buddy
get to carve another notch in your belt.

21:34.835 --> 21:36.420
Janet that's not really fair.

21:36.503 --> 21:38.046
This guy set a fire that killed a fireman.

21:38.130 --> 21:39.673
You don't think it's important
he's prosecuted?

21:39.798 --> 21:42.342
Whether it's important or not,
Lucy can't testify again.

21:42.467 --> 21:45.053
Your sister might be capable of more
than you give her credit for.

21:45.178 --> 21:47.848
Don't you dare presume
to tell me what my sister's capable of.

21:48.015 --> 21:50.142
You very nearly got her killed
this morning.

21:50.225 --> 21:51.685
-Stop it!
-(SIGHS)

21:51.768 --> 21:53.520
Darling, I don't want you
getting yourself worked up.

21:53.687 --> 21:55.647
He saved my life this morning,

21:55.772 --> 21:58.025
and I will not have you speak
to him like that.

21:58.567 --> 22:01.737
I'm sorry, perhaps you'd prefer
I didn't involve myself.

22:02.904 --> 22:04.197
Yes, I would.

22:05.657 --> 22:08.535
Fine. I guess you prefer
the company of policemen

22:08.702 --> 22:10.245
-to that of your sister.
-(SIGHS)

22:10.370 --> 22:12.414
-Janet.
-In any event, you're here with them.

22:12.581 --> 22:14.583
I'm sure you'll be perfectly safe.

22:19.212 --> 22:20.589
Why don't you take a few minutes?

22:23.091 --> 22:24.176
Don't be mad at her.

22:24.259 --> 22:25.802
No, she's worried about you.
I understand that.

22:26.219 --> 22:28.889
(SIGHS) It's just that it's all on me.

22:29.348 --> 22:31.683
I know you're there,
and I know Miss Munson's there,

22:31.767 --> 22:34.728
but sitting up there
on that witness stand,

22:35.228 --> 22:37.856
I feel like it's just me.

22:38.857 --> 22:40.859
Lucy, let's get a coffee. Come on.

22:46.698 --> 22:47.699
LUCY: Thank you.

22:48.909 --> 22:50.494
I know you're feeling
like you're alone in this,

22:50.577 --> 22:52.287
but you know that I care about you.

22:52.371 --> 22:54.206
-You know that I'm here to protect you.
-LUCY: Yes.

22:55.040 --> 22:56.458
You can't keep doing what you're doing.

22:57.542 --> 23:00.337
-What am I doing?
-Carrying secrets around with you.

23:00.670 --> 23:02.798
(STAMMERS) You're telling part truth,

23:02.923 --> 23:04.758
part lies, and hoping that
no one will find out

23:04.883 --> 23:07.094
what you don't want them to find out,
it's too much of a burden.

23:07.386 --> 23:08.720
What choice do I have?

23:09.763 --> 23:11.932
This morning, in Munson's office
you mentioned Ike Korensky,

23:12.099 --> 23:14.434
and then you pulled back
like you wished you hadn't mentioned him.

23:14.643 --> 23:17.229
Well, I wasn't aware of doing that.

23:17.562 --> 23:20.482
And then when you ran into him
on the stairs, you got so upset

23:20.649 --> 23:21.900
that you needed to see a doctor.

23:22.067 --> 23:24.444
That had nothing to do
with running into him.

23:24.528 --> 23:27.823
It was just a buildup
of everything that's been going on.

23:27.948 --> 23:30.450
-What was Ike's involvement, Lucy?
-Oh.

23:30.700 --> 23:32.244
Was he in on starting the fire?

23:32.452 --> 23:35.414
He did everything he could
to talk Sy out of it.

23:36.289 --> 23:39.042
He told him there were other ways
to come up with the money.

23:39.167 --> 23:42.379
He offered to sell his own home.
It didn't matter.

23:42.963 --> 23:45.257
When he saw that Sy was going
through with it,

23:45.674 --> 23:47.551
all he could do was go down
to the warehouse

23:47.676 --> 23:49.052
and give the guard the night off.

23:49.553 --> 23:51.513
-How do you know all this?
-Because Ike told me.

23:51.638 --> 23:54.182
-Why would he tell you?
-Because he trusted me.

23:55.142 --> 23:56.143
(SIGHS)

23:57.436 --> 23:59.104
And because we were lovers.

24:00.856 --> 24:05.068
He wasn't leaving his wife.
I knew he wasn't leaving his wife.

24:06.736 --> 24:08.822
I just loved him. (CHUCKLES)

24:10.157 --> 24:11.366
I still love him.

24:13.493 --> 24:15.203
(JOHN EXHALES)

24:20.083 --> 24:22.669
(UPBEAT MUSIC PLAYING)

24:27.632 --> 24:28.884
(MUSIC FADES)

24:29.092 --> 24:31.595
The auto squad ran the combinations
for that white Cadillac.

24:31.803 --> 24:34.973
They got six hits. It's our lucky day.
Only one of them is in the city.

24:35.140 --> 24:38.560
-Where are we going?
-Maxine Serasulo out in Rego Park.

24:39.019 --> 24:41.688
Let the boss know we had to go out.
We'll brief him when we get back.

24:41.980 --> 24:43.523
-I'll let him know.
-RITA: Thanks.

24:47.027 --> 24:48.153
This way.

24:52.699 --> 24:55.243
Normally, I got a lot of regard
for you guys, but this is nuts.

24:55.952 --> 24:57.704
How come you sent
the guard home that night, Ike?

24:57.871 --> 25:00.373
IKE: I sent him home
because there was nothing for him to do.

25:01.208 --> 25:03.168
I think that his daughter was up
from Florida then.

25:03.376 --> 25:05.587
You do realize it comes off
a little suspicious

25:05.754 --> 25:08.131
when you, all of a sudden,
send the night watchman home

25:08.256 --> 25:09.925
the same night the place burns down?

25:10.133 --> 25:13.386
Wolfe is my sister-in-law's father.
He couldn't guard a bowl of dog food.

25:13.512 --> 25:15.805
We kept him around so he could feel like
he was earning a few dollars.

25:15.931 --> 25:18.517
Ike, you discussed the plan ahead of time
with your brother.

25:18.642 --> 25:20.268
You went to the warehouse
the night of the fire.

25:20.435 --> 25:23.438
Believe me when I tell you,
there's 12 people in your future

25:23.563 --> 25:25.232
who are gonna send you to prison for that.

25:25.398 --> 25:27.150
How do you know what I discussed
with my brother?

25:27.275 --> 25:28.568
Lucy Welker told us.

25:28.777 --> 25:32.155
And when she takes the stand
the next time, she's gonna testify to it.

25:32.822 --> 25:34.282
And to how it is she knows.

25:34.699 --> 25:36.826
-She told you?
-JOHN: You should hang your head in shame

25:36.952 --> 25:38.620
that you let a scared-to-death woman

25:38.828 --> 25:41.790
that you supposedly care for,
put her life on the line

25:41.915 --> 25:45.168
because she's the only one willing
to stand up against your scumbag brother.

25:45.293 --> 25:46.461
I can't believe she told you.

25:46.545 --> 25:48.755
She stood the beating
without saying anything,

25:48.838 --> 25:50.840
but getting shot at was a little more
than she could handle.

25:50.924 --> 25:52.175
What do you think I wanted that?

25:52.300 --> 25:54.886
Doesn't matter what you wanted.
You did it to her.

25:55.053 --> 25:57.347
You and your brother did it big time
to that fireman.

25:57.430 --> 25:58.890
And you're going down for both of them.

25:58.974 --> 26:00.308
If you knew what I was going through...

26:00.392 --> 26:02.602
That is nothing compared
to what you're about to go through.

26:02.769 --> 26:06.940
You're going to prison, Ike.
You're gonna be tried as a co-conspirator.

26:07.148 --> 26:08.650
You will be convicted,

26:08.775 --> 26:13.321
and your kids are gonna grow up
seeing you every month behind plexiglass.

26:14.698 --> 26:16.825
-Unless you tell us the truth.
-(EXHALES NERVOUSLY)

26:18.159 --> 26:23.331
(PANTS)

26:26.001 --> 26:27.085
I can't do that.

26:28.920 --> 26:30.797
Take him downstairs. Throw him in a cell.

26:31.089 --> 26:32.424
-Get up. Let's go.
-(CHAIR SQUEAKS)

26:33.550 --> 26:36.011
(UPBEAT TENSE MUSIC PLAYING)

26:41.474 --> 26:42.892
(MUSIC FADES)

26:43.059 --> 26:44.811
What's your boyfriend's name,
Miss Serasulo?

26:46.062 --> 26:48.732
-Jeff Iaccanis.
-Why, what'd he do now?

26:49.524 --> 26:52.027
-When's the last time you saw him?
-This morning.

26:52.277 --> 26:53.528
Did he say what he was doing today?

26:53.903 --> 26:56.323
Yeah, he said he was going
to pick up some samples,

26:56.448 --> 26:57.949
like clothing samples,

26:58.033 --> 26:59.743
and he was taking them to this guy
who sells them

26:59.993 --> 27:02.037
at the flea market on 6th Avenue
on the weekends.

27:02.162 --> 27:04.581
That's why he needed the car,
and I had to take a bus to work.

27:04.873 --> 27:08.585
-You know if he was meeting anybody?
-I know he was going by Butchie's

27:09.169 --> 27:10.962
'cause he asked me for something
to bring over there.

27:11.087 --> 27:13.840
-What'd he ask you for?
-MAXINE: What's this about?

27:14.424 --> 27:15.717
We're just trying to gather information

27:15.842 --> 27:18.011
on what your boyfriend and Butchie
might have been doing today.

27:18.637 --> 27:20.847
He asked me for some pills
to bring Butchie's girlfriend.

27:21.056 --> 27:23.642
-Do you know where we can find Butchie?
-Not sure.

27:23.850 --> 27:26.978
(SIGHS) Oh,
we hate to have to tell you this,

27:27.479 --> 27:28.980
but your boyfriend was killed today.

27:29.356 --> 27:30.774
(SCOFFS) Great.

27:32.901 --> 27:35.195
If you want to take a few minutes
to compose yourself, feel free.

27:35.779 --> 27:36.780
How'd it happen?

27:37.530 --> 27:40.575
He was in the midst of committing a crime,
and he was killed by a police officer.

27:41.242 --> 27:42.327
Asshole.

27:42.744 --> 27:44.704
LAURA: You think Butchie was with him
when this happened?

27:45.080 --> 27:46.081
Of course.

27:46.748 --> 27:49.209
You should know that Butchie
drove off and left him to die in street.

27:50.502 --> 27:52.420
Butchie was driving my car?

27:52.629 --> 27:55.173
-RITA: Right.
-Son of a bitch!

27:55.715 --> 27:58.385
Jeff told me it was only him
who was gonna be driving my car.

27:58.635 --> 28:00.220
I don't let Butchie drive my car.

28:00.387 --> 28:02.347
I mean, no matter what,
I don't let Butchie drive my car.

28:02.514 --> 28:03.848
We need to find Butchie.

28:04.683 --> 28:07.018
First block of Yellowstone Boulevard
off the expressway.

28:07.227 --> 28:09.104
There's a two-family house
with a pink and white awning.

28:09.229 --> 28:11.106
Butchie's around the back on the right.

28:11.189 --> 28:13.817
And there'd better be no damage
to that Cadillac car,

28:14.025 --> 28:16.277
or you can tell Butchie
he's gonna make good on it.

28:16.444 --> 28:19.447
-I don't care if he's in prison or not.
-We'll definitely tell him.

28:19.572 --> 28:22.242
Some stupid idiot,
I pick for a boyfriend, huh?

28:23.076 --> 28:24.285
(SOBS)

28:26.663 --> 28:28.248
(SOBS)

28:29.457 --> 28:31.126
(INTENSE MUSIC PLAYING)

28:36.548 --> 28:37.716
(MUSIC FADES)

28:37.799 --> 28:38.842
(SIGHS)

28:39.092 --> 28:40.927
ANDY: That thing with Michael's
this afternoon?

28:41.553 --> 28:43.471
-Yeah.
-ANDY: How's it look?

28:44.222 --> 28:45.682
The lawyer says it could go either way.

28:48.309 --> 28:49.936
I had a conversation with Gary Moretti.

28:51.312 --> 28:53.398
-Yeah?
-You don't want to do this.

28:53.481 --> 28:54.899
I don't know what you're talking about.

28:55.066 --> 28:57.444
You worked hard to build
the kind of reputation you got.

28:57.610 --> 28:59.571
One bonehead move like this,
and it's gone.

29:02.407 --> 29:05.201
You'd do anything for your kid, right?
Michael's my kid.

29:05.577 --> 29:07.912
-Let this play itself out, Baldwin.
-BALDWIN: What does that mean?

29:08.288 --> 29:09.372
What, trust the system?

29:09.748 --> 29:11.708
This guy kills his wife,
then gets away with it.

29:12.083 --> 29:14.419
He snows the judge into granting
him supervised visitation.

29:14.711 --> 29:16.296
Now he's bucking for full custody.

29:16.504 --> 29:18.381
I'm not saying to sit back and do nothing.

29:18.465 --> 29:21.050
No, no, no. Which he actually might get,
'cause the judge could find that

29:21.217 --> 29:22.927
being with his murdering,
dope fiend of a father

29:23.011 --> 29:26.306
-is somehow in Michael's best interest.
-Or that might not be what happens.

29:27.807 --> 29:29.851
I gave Michael my word
he wouldn't go back to his father.

29:30.018 --> 29:31.227
I made a promise.

29:31.394 --> 29:33.730
You also made a promise
to stay in his life.

29:33.897 --> 29:35.899
You get yourself locked up
or fired off the job,

29:35.982 --> 29:37.567
they're taking him away
from you no matter what.

29:37.650 --> 29:39.277
Yeah, and putting him
with another foster parent.

29:39.444 --> 29:40.904
-The point being he's not with you.
-No.

29:41.070 --> 29:44.741
The point being they put him
back with his father, he winds up dead.

29:51.331 --> 29:53.249
(SIGHS) Weight of the world.

29:56.419 --> 29:59.547
Uh, how... how's the studying coming
for the sergeant's test?

30:00.006 --> 30:01.007
ANDY: Good.

30:02.967 --> 30:07.889
Do not, under any circumstances,
neglect aided-cases procedures.

30:08.515 --> 30:09.766
Yeah, I'm going over all of that.

30:09.849 --> 30:13.937
Yeah, one thing to remember,
a prisoner is never an aided case.

30:14.771 --> 30:17.148
I... I try to use mnemonics.

30:17.357 --> 30:19.692
-You know what I mean by "mnemonics"?
-Not exactly.

30:21.194 --> 30:25.406
"My Very Educated Mother
Just Served Us Nine Pickles."

30:26.032 --> 30:29.702
Mercury, Venus, Earth, Mars, Jupiter...

30:29.828 --> 30:32.288
Yeah, right,
I, uh, I haven't found any of them yet.

30:33.790 --> 30:37.585
You know, I... I wish
I'd have kept my 3x5 file cards.

30:37.877 --> 30:40.463
I was so disgusted
when I got out of the exam,

30:40.588 --> 30:41.589
I threw them all away.

30:41.714 --> 30:42.799
-(PHONE RINGING)
-Oh, yeah.

30:42.882 --> 30:46.761
GREG: I went blank, pouring sweat,
my stomach doing flip-flops.

30:47.011 --> 30:48.555
I could barely remember my own name.

30:48.888 --> 30:50.515
-Guess that can happen.
-JOHN: Excuse me,

30:50.640 --> 30:54.102
that was the desk sergeant.
Ike Korensky, just tried to hang himself.

30:56.020 --> 30:57.814
(OMINOUS MUSIC PLAYING)

31:04.070 --> 31:05.947
-MALE VOICE: He's still breathing.
-What'd he do it with?

31:06.030 --> 31:08.616
His shirt. I took his belt.
I took his shoelaces.

31:08.783 --> 31:10.201
When's the last time you looked in on him?

31:10.285 --> 31:13.580
Ten minutes ago. He was fine.
He asked about getting something to eat.

31:13.955 --> 31:16.207
I want a cop riding
in the ambulance with him.

31:16.833 --> 31:18.585
-Is he gonna make it?
-FEMALE VOICE: I don't know.

31:19.168 --> 31:21.379
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

31:24.883 --> 31:26.467
(MUSIC FADES)

31:28.136 --> 31:29.345
(INTENSE MUSIC PLAYING)

31:33.725 --> 31:34.851
(MUSIC FADES)

31:34.976 --> 31:36.895
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

31:37.145 --> 31:40.231
-It figures it didn't work.
-You think maybe that's a good thing?

31:41.024 --> 31:43.776
-You don't understand.
-ANDY: Help us with it, then, Ike.

31:44.193 --> 31:46.821
Tell us how it is that, uh,
your wife deserves to be a widow,

31:46.946 --> 31:49.574
and your kids deserve
to be left without a father.

31:51.451 --> 31:54.078
-They're better off without me.
-They don't think so.

31:54.245 --> 31:56.456
IKE: Now they don't think so.
Let them see the mess I'm in.

31:57.206 --> 32:00.752
The kind of person that I am.
They'll only wish I'd done it sooner.

32:01.085 --> 32:03.004
-You're wrong.
-IKE: You're young still.

32:03.671 --> 32:06.341
Believe me, you don't always
do people a favor by staying alive.

32:08.051 --> 32:09.886
My father killed himself, Ike.

32:10.303 --> 32:12.722
He had all kinds of problems.
He made all kinds of mess.

32:13.181 --> 32:15.516
Never once did I think I was better off.

32:17.685 --> 32:19.437
I'm sorry you're having
to go through that...

32:20.897 --> 32:22.231
and I didn't know your father.

32:24.817 --> 32:26.194
But I know that in my community,

32:26.611 --> 32:28.613
the lowest thing that you can do
is turn on your family,

32:29.113 --> 32:30.990
on your brother. How can I face him?

32:31.115 --> 32:33.618
How can you face the woman
that your brother tried to kill?

32:36.287 --> 32:37.372
I can't.

32:38.748 --> 32:40.959
Maybe you've been given
another chance so you can.

32:41.459 --> 32:42.710
(SIGHS)

32:44.379 --> 32:46.130
(INTENSE MUSIC PLAYING)

32:50.635 --> 32:51.761
(MUSIC FADES)

32:51.970 --> 32:53.429
RITA: Where were you
this morning, Butchie?

32:53.638 --> 32:56.391
Uh, let me think a second,
'cause I want to get this right.

32:56.683 --> 32:59.686
Uh, this morning, uh,
I had coffee with my girlfriend,

32:59.978 --> 33:01.854
my fiancÃ©e, actually.

33:04.524 --> 33:06.526
-Then I went into the city.
-How'd you get there?

33:06.693 --> 33:08.486
"F" train on Continental Avenue.

33:08.736 --> 33:10.655
Well, we have information
that you and another individual

33:10.738 --> 33:12.573
were seen in a car
at some point this morning.

33:12.699 --> 33:15.326
I... I might have driven over
to Continental Avenue.

33:15.702 --> 33:18.329
-Who was this individual, Butchie?
-He's a friend of mine.

33:18.454 --> 33:20.081
-Where is he now?
-I don't know.

33:20.373 --> 33:22.458
-We think maybe you do know, Butchie.
-No, I don't.

33:22.583 --> 33:24.460
Would you like us to take you
to where he is now

33:24.544 --> 33:25.837
and show him to you?

33:26.879 --> 33:29.173
I was getting a ride into the city
is all I was doing.

33:29.298 --> 33:31.843
And along the way, he decided
to stop off and kill somebody,

33:31.926 --> 33:33.136
so he asked you to drive?

33:33.261 --> 33:35.638
You shouldn't have too tough
of a time getting a jury to buy that.

33:35.888 --> 33:37.557
You guys think I'm a hit man?

33:38.016 --> 33:40.184
The kind of crimes I do,
I grab a handful of fake Rolexes

33:40.268 --> 33:43.229
off some wink's table on Canal Street,
and I sell them for 15 dollars a piece.

33:43.354 --> 33:46.232
Well, then congratulations,
you've just broken into the big leagues.

33:46.441 --> 33:48.735
What you're looking at
is conspiracy to commit murder

33:48.860 --> 33:50.737
and attempted murder on a police officer.

33:50.862 --> 33:53.197
That'll send you away
for 25 years minimum.

33:53.322 --> 33:55.491
On the other hand,
it'll look a lot more impressive in prison

33:55.575 --> 33:57.744
-than grabbing a handful of fake Rolexes.
-BUTCHIE: Wait a minute.

33:57.827 --> 34:00.204
I didn't shoot the gun!
I didn't touch the gun!

34:00.455 --> 34:01.622
All I did was drive.

34:01.706 --> 34:03.583
For a murder conspiracy, driving's enough.

34:03.791 --> 34:05.168
LAURA: Who's Jeff working for, Butchie?

34:05.334 --> 34:07.754
Right, right.
So now I tell you that, I'm dead.

34:07.962 --> 34:10.631
Tell us what happened,
you'll be provided with protection.

34:10.840 --> 34:12.800
Oh, like that lady was provided
with protection.

34:13.051 --> 34:14.552
That woman's alive and unharmed.

34:14.927 --> 34:17.680
But if you think it's too much of a risk,
we'll just mark you down as uncooperative,

34:17.764 --> 34:20.641
turn it over to the DA,
and you could take your chance in court.

34:25.354 --> 34:27.482
He was working for this guy Korensky.

34:27.690 --> 34:29.358
Jeff was getting 20,
and I was getting ten.

34:29.442 --> 34:30.443
LAURA: Good.

34:32.862 --> 34:36.157
All I wanted to do today was get high
and just stay in bed with my girlfriend.

34:38.409 --> 34:40.161
(UPBEAT MUSIC PLAYING)

34:45.833 --> 34:47.085
(MUSIC FADES)

34:47.251 --> 34:49.921
-JUDGE KOLISCH: You're late, detective.
-I'm sorry, Your Honor.

34:50.088 --> 34:52.298
And you were supposed
to have brought Michael with you.

34:52.548 --> 34:53.549
Where is he?

34:54.592 --> 34:56.803
He left school sometime
after second period.

34:56.886 --> 34:58.721
-I don't know where he is.
-I was waiting for this.

34:58.888 --> 35:00.056
That's enough, Mr. Woodruff.

35:00.473 --> 35:02.475
I checked out the house.
I checked with his aunt.

35:02.767 --> 35:05.103
I called his friends.
Nobody seems to know where he is.

35:05.353 --> 35:08.064
I would ask that at a minimum
the current foster-care placement

35:08.272 --> 35:10.066
of Michael with Detective Jones
be terminated.

35:10.191 --> 35:13.736
-There is no basis for this, Your Honor.
-The basis is that either Detective Jones

35:13.820 --> 35:15.738
is actively concealing
Michael's whereabouts

35:15.822 --> 35:17.490
because he's afraid
he's not gonna like the outcome

35:17.573 --> 35:19.033
of these proceedings, or he's negligent.

35:19.367 --> 35:21.828
In either case, he ought not to remain
as the adult responsible

35:21.911 --> 35:22.995
for this boy's well-being.

35:23.079 --> 35:25.665
JUDGE KOLISCH: Miss Friedman,
I am not getting into that, right now.

35:25.790 --> 35:29.001
The boy's not here, I'm not gonna proceed
with this hearing until he is here.

35:29.210 --> 35:32.255
And so what I would suggest,
is that everyone lend their best efforts

35:32.421 --> 35:34.590
to finding him and bringing him in.

35:35.091 --> 35:37.635
Miss Kingston, I trust you'll be playing
an active role in that.

35:37.844 --> 35:38.928
I will, Your Honor.

35:39.095 --> 35:41.264
The court is to be informed
when the boy surfaces.

35:41.389 --> 35:42.807
Until then, we're adjourned.

35:45.184 --> 35:48.396
(DOOR OPENS, SHUTS)

35:48.521 --> 35:51.357
Why is it you guys are all about
abiding by the law,

35:51.482 --> 35:53.860
respecting the law, until it looks like
it's going against you?

35:53.943 --> 35:55.528
I don't want to get
into this with you, Craig.

35:55.653 --> 35:56.696
CRAIG: No, I bet you don't.

35:56.946 --> 35:59.031
It can't be all that easy to look
a boy's father in the face

35:59.198 --> 36:00.658
and tell him that
you made off with his son.

36:00.741 --> 36:02.326
Come on, Craig.
This isn't the place to do this.

36:02.493 --> 36:05.037
-I don't think of you as a father.
-I know you don't, but that's what I am.

36:05.413 --> 36:07.623
It doesn't matter whether you think
of me that way or not.

36:07.748 --> 36:09.417
I am Michael's father.

36:09.917 --> 36:13.796
-I am. Not you, me.
-You need to stop this now.

36:13.921 --> 36:16.215
Bring him back, you hear me?
Bring him back, or I'm gonna forget

36:16.465 --> 36:18.885
that I'm a Christian man,
that I abide by the law,

36:18.968 --> 36:19.969
and I'm gonna come after you.

36:20.094 --> 36:21.804
Hey! You need to control your client,
Miss Friedman.

36:21.929 --> 36:24.056
-Craig, it's enough now.
-CRAIG: Whatever happens to me,

36:24.390 --> 36:25.474
I'm gonna come after you.

36:28.352 --> 36:29.604
(PENSIVE MUSIC PLAYING)

36:36.319 --> 36:37.486
(DOOR SHUTS)

36:38.988 --> 36:42.325
Baldwin... Baldwin, listen to me.

36:48.247 --> 36:49.665
I can protect you if you have him,

36:49.749 --> 36:52.126
but you have to put him in a cab
and send him over to my office.

36:52.251 --> 36:55.546
Look, I don't have him. I don't have time
to convince you and tell you the truth,

36:55.713 --> 36:57.465
and I don't care
whether you believe me or not.

36:57.924 --> 36:59.550
He ran away. I don't know where he is.

37:01.844 --> 37:05.097
-You have any idea where he is?
-No.

37:07.516 --> 37:08.851
You have my cellphone number.

37:09.060 --> 37:10.686
Will you call me as soon
as you know something?

37:11.270 --> 37:12.355
(SIGHS) Yeah.

37:12.438 --> 37:14.815
Well, let me go back in there
and try to talk to them.

37:14.982 --> 37:16.067
BALDWIN: Hey, one minute.

37:18.986 --> 37:20.488
I'm sorry about this morning.

37:21.656 --> 37:24.367
Okay. Go find him.

37:27.286 --> 37:31.165
(UPBEAT MUSIC PLAYING)

37:31.540 --> 37:34.126
I appreciate your coming by,
Mr. Kerasic.

37:34.293 --> 37:35.586
You made the decision to go to trial?

37:36.545 --> 37:37.755
-(DOOR SHUTS)
-GREG: I did.

37:37.880 --> 37:39.799
NORMAN: Then you're entitled
to competent representation,

37:39.924 --> 37:41.634
which, that would be me.

37:42.009 --> 37:44.178
Yeah, yeah, they said you were good.

37:44.679 --> 37:46.806
People think you gotta go
with outside counsel to have a chance.

37:46.931 --> 37:49.934
That's baloney.
I hold my own against any of those guys.

37:50.393 --> 37:51.727
-Good.
-And then some.

37:52.103 --> 37:54.647
Hmm. Uh, obviously, it's not an issue

37:54.981 --> 37:57.483
-whether or not I was working at the bar.
-Concede nothing.

37:57.775 --> 38:00.695
No, I'm just saying
that, uh, they can prove it.

38:00.778 --> 38:02.655
I mean, there's no question with it,
they can prove it.

38:02.738 --> 38:05.908
-NORMAN: Right.
-Yeah, so then, uh, what do we do?

38:06.450 --> 38:08.119
We keep it short and sweet.

38:08.494 --> 38:10.162
They'll have your record in front of them.

38:10.413 --> 38:13.082
They'll be made aware by me
of the disproportionate nature

38:13.249 --> 38:14.542
of the suggested punishment.

38:15.293 --> 38:17.962
I enjoy a good relationship
with most of the trial commissioners.

38:18.129 --> 38:19.380
Hopefully, the one we get

38:19.463 --> 38:21.257
won't be fresh out of human kindness
when he rules.

38:21.424 --> 38:25.261
Yeah, and, uh, you don't think
it's a bad idea going to trial?

38:25.636 --> 38:26.804
I think it's a terrible idea.

38:27.430 --> 38:30.599
But that's what you want to do,
so that's what we're doing.

38:33.936 --> 38:35.855
(UPBEAT MUSIC PLAYING)

38:42.403 --> 38:43.779
(MUSIC FADES)

38:44.155 --> 38:46.449
-Where is she?
-In the coffee room with Rita.

38:49.243 --> 38:51.787
-Miller, put him in the pokey.
-You got it.

38:51.954 --> 38:55.833
-I want to call my lawyer to meet me here.
-There's nothing he can do for you here.

38:55.958 --> 38:57.585
Have him meet you at 100 Centre Street.

38:57.710 --> 38:59.420
-How long?
-Two hours.

38:59.879 --> 39:02.631
-I don't want to wait two hours!
-You have no choice.

39:06.927 --> 39:10.139
-We just brought him in.
-Good work. Maybe this time it'll stick.

39:10.431 --> 39:11.432
Let's hope.

39:11.807 --> 39:13.517
You're taking the sergeant's test
next Saturday?

39:14.018 --> 39:15.561
(SIGHS) Yeah.

39:16.062 --> 39:18.272
-I'll clear you for the day.
-Thanks.

39:19.565 --> 39:21.609
Why don't you take my copy
of the Patrol Guide?

39:21.817 --> 39:24.278
-That's all right. I got one.
-Mine's got all my notes in it.

39:25.738 --> 39:28.074
Okay. Thank you.

39:30.576 --> 39:31.577
THOMAS: Good luck.

39:37.375 --> 39:39.585
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

39:40.461 --> 39:42.838
Detective, is he here?

39:43.422 --> 39:45.049
(CLEARS THROAT) He's in the pokey.

39:45.216 --> 39:47.176
-LORI: Where's Lucy?
-This way.

39:54.850 --> 39:56.811
Now you can hear it from the DA herself.

39:56.936 --> 39:58.854
You're testifying, Ike's testifying,

39:58.938 --> 40:01.148
and the guy who drove the car
this morning is testifying.

40:01.273 --> 40:04.276
-Safety in numbers maybe.
-He can't make all three of you disappear.

40:04.527 --> 40:06.362
Simon Korensky will die in prison, Lucy.

40:06.529 --> 40:09.073
That's not necessarily something
I would wish on anyone.

40:09.240 --> 40:11.951
-In his case, you can make an exception.
-(LORI CHUCKLES)

40:12.076 --> 40:13.869
Would it be all right
if I went to see Ike?

40:15.579 --> 40:17.665
Sure. We can run you over there.

40:22.503 --> 40:24.046
LUCY: Thank you. (CHUCKLES)

40:29.593 --> 40:32.304
-We should go start the paperwork.
-Can I have him for one second?

40:34.432 --> 40:35.766
I'll go start the paperwork.

40:38.727 --> 40:40.771
Whatever I thought about you
going into this case,

40:41.063 --> 40:42.982
I just want to say "Thank you,"
for everything you did.

40:43.649 --> 40:47.236
And whatever you thought about me,
you were absolutely right to think.

40:47.862 --> 40:49.655
This is one I don't want to lose.

40:49.864 --> 40:51.365
As opposed to ones where you don't mind?

40:51.699 --> 40:54.160
You're right,
I don't like to lose any of them.

40:55.536 --> 40:57.997
-It was good working with you.
-It was good working with you.

41:00.875 --> 41:04.211
(PENSIVE MUSIC PLAYING)

41:12.845 --> 41:14.013
(MUSIC FADES)

41:14.138 --> 41:15.222
What happened?

41:15.306 --> 41:17.475
Michael went missing from school
before I could pick him up.

41:17.600 --> 41:20.311
-GREG: You haven't heard from him?
-I checked everywhere I could think of.

41:20.728 --> 41:22.897
-He ever do this before?
-Never.

41:23.022 --> 41:25.483
-(SIGHS) You want to find him fast.
-BALDWIN: Yeah. No kidding.

41:25.566 --> 41:27.109
-JOHN: You have his cellphone?
-Yeah.

41:27.234 --> 41:28.819
Get it dumped and maybe try
and get it cloned.

41:28.944 --> 41:30.863
Without a court order,
that's not gonna happen.

41:31.071 --> 41:32.948
GREG: You got a good photograph
of him in your locker?

41:33.032 --> 41:34.825
-Yeah.
-Should I make up some flyers?

41:35.034 --> 41:36.452
GREG: Right, and get them out to patrol.

41:36.577 --> 41:38.329
Put an F.A.T.N. message out
to all commands.

41:38.579 --> 41:40.789
Also, give us a list of places
he hangs out at.

41:40.998 --> 41:42.833
All right, I'll go get the photograph.

41:45.294 --> 41:47.630
-Can you tell the boss?
-Right.

41:53.802 --> 41:55.346
I gotta ask you this.

41:56.096 --> 41:57.556
I don't have him, Andy.

41:57.723 --> 42:00.017
I'd understand it
if you hid him away someplace.

42:01.352 --> 42:02.478
I wish I did...

42:04.480 --> 42:05.814
'cause depending on what happens,

42:05.940 --> 42:08.150
I may spend the rest of my life
regretting that I didn't.

42:14.031 --> 42:16.951
-I'll check with Port Authority Police.
-Thanks.

42:17.451 --> 42:19.203
-He'll turn up.
-Yeah.

42:20.955 --> 42:23.499
(PENSIVE MUSIC PLAYING)

42:26.794 --> 42:28.087
(DOOR SHUTS)

42:40.766 --> 42:42.810
(MUSIC FADES)

42:44.728 --> 42:47.982
(THEME MUSIC PLAYING)

43:12.464 --> 43:14.300
(THEME MUSIC FADES)
